In the context of [[Sovereign default|sovereign debt crisis]], '''private sector involvement''' ('''PSI''') refers, broadly speaking, to the contributions or efforts of [[private sector]] creditors to the crisis resolution process, and, specifically, means that the private sector shares some of the costs of a [[financial crisis]] by incurring itself financial losses.<ref name=refers>{{cite journal|url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/pub/pdf/scpops/ecbocp32.pdf |last=|first= |last2= |first2= |last3=|first3=|date=July 2005 |title= Managing Financial Crises in Emerging Market-Economies: Experience with the Involvement of Private Sector Creditors|journal=Occasional Paper Series|publisher=[[European Central Bank|ECB]]|volume=|issue=32 |pages=|bibcode= |access-date=30 June 2018}}</ref>{{rp|6}} ==History== The term "private sector involvement" was introduced in the late-1990s in the context of the discussions on [[bond (finance)|bond]] restructurings and [[capital account]] crises.<ref name=refers/>{{rp|6}}
Previously, the term used to broadly denote any kind of private-sector participation into an existing government program, such as, for example, [[family planning]],<ref>[http://www.cpc.unc.edu/measure/prh/rh_indicators/crosscutting/ps "Private Sector Involvement in Family Planning"], the Family Planning and Reproductive Health Indicators Database</ref> or [[health care]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kirkpatrick|first1=Ian |last2=McCabe |first2=Christopher |date=12 April 2011|title=The NHS braces itself for privatisation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/apr/12/private-sector-involvement-nhs |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref> Since then, it has come to signify specifically the private sector's participation in the losses taken in cases of [[sovereign debt]] [[write down]]s.<ref name=cline>{{cite journal |last=Cline |first=William R. |last2=|first2= |last3=|first3=|date=November 2002 |url=https://www.cgdev.org/sites/default/files/2772_file_cgd_wp018.pdf|title=Private Sector Involvement in Financial Crisis Resolution: Definition, Measurement, and Implementation |journal=Working Papers|publisher=[[Center for Global Development]] |volume=|issue=18 |pages= |bibcode=|doi=|access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=imf1>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=J5otDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:1475539061&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIwZHAgNvbAhWCIlAKHfMEBFAQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Portugal : Ex Post Evaluation of Exceptional Access Under the 2011 Extended Arrangement|last= |first=|series=Country Report No. 16/302 |publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]]|date=September 2016 |website= |access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=swap>{{cite web |url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2017/11/30/to-swap-or-not-to-swap-greece-issues-5-new-bonds/|title=To swap or not to swap? Greece issues 5 new bonds |last=Pelagidis |first=Theodore |publisher=[[Brookings Institution]] |date=30 November 2017 |website= |access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref>
==Justification== The private sector involvements covers measures such as the rescheduling, reprofiling, and restructuring of the state-debt holdings of private creditors, in the context of the resolution of a sovereign debt crisis.<ref name=bulletin>{{cite journal|url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/pub/pdf/mobu/mb201110en.pdf |last=|first= |last2= |first2= |last3=|first3=|date=October 2011 |title=Private sector involvement and its financial stability implications |journal=Monthly Bulletin|publisher=[[European Central Bank|ECB]]|volume= |pages=43-49 |bibcode= |access-date=30 June 2018}}</ref>{{rp|43}} According to the [[International Monetary Fund]], the measures of the private sector involvement process are appropriate in order to "have the burden of crisis resolution shared equitably with the [state] sector," as well as to "strengthen market discipline."<ref name=imf2/> ==Implications== ECB Executive Board member [[Lorenzo Bini Smaghi]] has warned in 2011 that the enforcement of private sector involvement in resolving a financial crisis inside the [[Eurozone]] would incur "a series of problems": The taxpayers of the creditor countries would suffer in any case; patient investors, who have stuck to their investment, would be punished; the measure would destabilize the financial markets of the Eurozone by creating incentives for short-term speculative behavior; and it would delay the return of the debtor nation to the markets since market participants would be unwilling to start reinvesting in the country for a long period. This, Smaghi stated, would oblige the state sector to eventually increase its financial contribution.<ref name=smaghi>{{cite web |url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/key/date/2011/html/sp110606.en.html|title=Private sector involvement: From (good) theory to (bad) practice|last=Bini Smaghi |first=Lorenzo|author-link=Lorenzo Bini Smaghi|publisher=[[European Central Bank|ECB]] |date=6 June 2011 |website=Speech at the Reinventing Bretton Woods Committee|access-date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>
==Context== Although the term used to denote any kind of private-sector participation into an existing government program, such as, for example, [[family planning]],<ref>[http://www.cpc.unc.edu/measure/prh/rh_indicators/crosscutting/ps "Private Sector Involvement in Family Planning"], the Family Planning and Reproductive Health Indicators Database</ref> or [[health care]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kirkpatrick|first1=Ian |last2=McCabe |first2=Christopher |date=12 April 2011|title=The NHS braces itself for privatisation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/apr/12/private-sector-involvement-nhs |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref> it has come to signify the private sector's participation in the losses taken in cases of [[sovereign debt]] [[write down]]s,<ref name=cline>{{cite journal |last=Cline |first=William R. |last2=|first2= |last3=|first3=|date=November 2002 |url=https://www.cgdev.org/sites/default/files/2772_file_cgd_wp018.pdf|title=Private Sector Involvement in Financial Crisis Resolution: Definition, Measurement, and Implementation |journal=Working Papers|publisher=[[Center for Global Development]] |volume=|issue=18 |pages= |bibcode=|doi=|access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=imf1>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=J5otDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:1475539061&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIwZHAgNvbAhWCIlAKHfMEBFAQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Portugal : Ex Post Evaluation of Exceptional Access Under the 2011 Extended Arrangement|last= |first=|series=Country Report No. 16/302 |publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]]|date=September 2016 |website= |access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=swap>{{cite web |url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2017/11/30/to-swap-or-not-to-swap-greece-issues-5-new-bonds/|title=To swap or not to swap? Greece issues 5 new bonds |last=Pelagidis |first=Theodore |publisher=[[Brookings Institution]] |date=30 November 2017 |website= |access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref> and, more specifically, "any kind of...contributions of the private sector in the context of sovereign financial distress."<ref name=sense>{{cite journal |last=Enderlein |first=Henrik |last2= Müller|first2=Laura |last3=Trebesch |first3=Christoph |date=8 September 2006 |url=http://www.sfb-governance.de/teilprojekte/projekte_phase_1/projektbereich_d/d4/Enderlein_M__ller_Trebesch__Garnetconf_2006.pdf|title=Making Sense of PSI : On the role of the private sector in sovereign debt crises |journal=|publisher=Hertie School of Governance|place=Berlin |volume= |pages= |bibcode=|doi=}}</ref>
In the view of the [[International Monetary Fund]], private sector involvement "in the resolution of financial crises is appropriate in order to have the burden of crisis resolution shared equitably with the official sector, strengthen market discipline, and, in the process, increase the efficiency of international capital markets and the ability of emerging market borrowers to protect themselves against volatility and contagion."<ref name=imf2>{{cite web |url=https://www.imf.org/external/np/exr/facts/privsec.htm|title=The IMF and the Private Sector|last= |first=|publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]]|date=August 2001 |website= |access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref> The Fund claims that "a broad consensus has emerged among IMF member countries on the need to seek PSI in the resolution of crises."<ref name=imf2/> According to [[William R. Cline]], “'PSI' has been the 1990s equivalent of 'bailing in the banks' in the 1980s."<ref name=cline/>
==Greek sovereign-debt crisis== The most prominent case of PSI occurred in the process of the sovereign-debt restructuring of [[Greece]], after a significant [[Haircut (finance)|haircut]]<ref group=note>"Haircut: A reduction in the [[face value]] of a troubled borrower's debts ([https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-33311405 BBC], 2015); a reduction of the amount that will be repaid to creditors ([https://www.cnbc.com/2015/08/19/why-the-imf-is-wrong-on-a-greek-debt-haircut.html CNBC], 2015)</ref> of it was [[Greek_government_debt_crisis#Second_rescue_package_.28July_2011_-_February_2012.29|agreed]], in early 2012. The so-called "world's biggest debt-restructuring deal in history"<ref name=how>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/02/29/us-europe-greece-idUSTRE81S0NP20120229 "How the Greek debt puzzle was solved"], Reuters, 29 February 2012</ref><ref name=concedes/>{{rp|1}} affecting some €206bn of bonds, occurred in February 2012, when the [[Eurogroup]] finalized a second [[Greek government-debt crisis|bailout package for Greece]].<ref name=group>[http://consilium.europa.eu/uedocs/cms_data/docs/pressdata/en/ecofin/128075.pdf Statement] by the [[Eurogroup]], 21 February 2012</ref>
[[European Union|EU]] member-states agreed to a new €100 billion loan and a retroactive lowering of the bailout interest rates, while the [[International Monetary Fund]] would provide "a significant contribution" to that loan.<ref name=group /> Part of that deal was the agreement for private-sector involvement (PSI), whereby private investors were asked to accept to write off 53.5% of the face value of the Greek governmental bonds they're holding, the equivalent to an overall loss of around 75%.<Ref name=group />
If not enough private-sector bondholders were to agree to participate in the bond swap per the PSI requirement, the Greek government threatened to retroactively introduce a [[collective action clause]] to enforce participation.<ref name=sud>[http://www.sueddeutsche.de/wirtschaft/geld-fuer-griechenland-freigegeben-das-rettungspaket-kommt-die-zweifel-bleiben-1.1289418 "Das Rettungspaket kommt, die Zweifel bleiben"] ("The bailout comes, the doubts remain"), ''[[Süddeutsche Zeitung]]'', 21 February 2012, (in German)</ref> Eventually, private-sector involvement reached 83,5% of Greek bond holders.<ref>[http://www.iif.com/press/press+239.php Statement] by [[Charles Dallara]] and [[Jean Lemierre]], Co-Chairs, Steering Committee of the Private Creditor-Investor Committee for Greece, [[Institute of International Finance]], 9 March 2012</ref> The [[Bank of Greece]], in its 2011/12 report, commented that "the successful completion of the PSI, creates a new operating framework for the Greek economy in the years ahead."<ref>"[https://www.bankofgreece.gr/pages/en/bank/news/pressreleases/DispItem.aspx?Item_ID=3882&List_ID=1af869f3-57fb-4de6-b9ae-bdfd83c66c95&Filter_by=DT The Bank of Greece Report on Monetary Policy 2011-2012]", [[Bank of Greece]], 19 March 2012</ref>
==Legal aspects== Certain official measures executed during Greece's state debt restructuring process and the subsequent private sector involvement were not covered by existing [[International Swaps and Derivatives Association|ISDA]] provisions for [[Credit default swap|CDS]] contracts, as the [[International Monetary Fund]] conceded.<ref name=concedes>{{cite journal |last=Liu |first=Yan |last2=Bergthaler |first2=Wolfgang |last3=Giddings |first3=Andrew |last4=Kosonen |first4=Amanda|last5=Papaioannou|first5=Michael|last6=Grigorian |first6=David |last7= Guscina |first7=Anastasia |last8=Presciuttini |first8=Gabriel |last9=Tsuda|first9=Takahiro |last10=Baqir |first10= Reza |url=https://www.imf.org/external/np/pp/eng/2013/042613.pdf|journal=Policy Papers|publisher=[[IMF]]| |date=26 April 2013|title=Sovereign Debt Restructuring: Recent Developments and Implications|volume= |pages= |access-date=30 June 2018}}</ref>{{rp|33}}
Therefore, according to the IMF, the typically expected [[credit event]] was not officially triggered, the negative contingencies to private holders of state debt were increased, while the credibility of the sovereign-[[Credit default swap|CDS]] market was undermined. The measures undertaken included the "persuasion"<ref group=note name=marks>Quotation marks in the original.</ref><ref name=concedes/>{{rp|33}} of certain Greek debt-holders to accept large [[Haircut (finance)|haircuts]] under a supposedly “voluntary PSI" agreement.<ref group=note name=marks/><ref name=concedes/>{{rp|33}} Accordingly, Greece achieved a "very high creditor participation" of 97 percent of debt held, despite the restructuring being preemptive and, as assessed by the IMF, having a "very large" target of a 70 percent [[haircut (finance)|haircut]] of the bonds' [[face value]].<ref group=note>In terms of [[net present value]].</ref><ref name=concedes/>{{rp|27}}
==See also== *[[Bailout]] *[[European sovereign-debt crisis: List of acronyms]] ==Notes== {{reflist|group=note}} ==References== {{reflist}} ==External links== *{{cite journal |last= Xafa |first= Miranda |last2=|first2= |last3= |first3= |date=January–March 2013 |url=https://www.mirandaxafa.com/mediaupload/articles/life_after_debt.pdf|title=Life after Debt : The Greek PSI and its aftermath |journal=World Economics|volume=14|issue=1 |pages=81-102 |bibcode=|doi=}}
